<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,467,397,423]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A member of the 
<taxonomicName box="[674,865,398,424]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spanglerorum">
<emphasis box="[674,865,398,424]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. spanglerorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group, differentiated from the other members (
<taxonomicName box="[214,404,432,458]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spanglerorum">
<emphasis box="[214,404,432,458]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. spanglerorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2021" box="[457,586,432,458]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colossus">
<emphasis box="[457,586,432,458]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. colossus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) by the combination of slightly smaller size (ca. 
<quantity box="[1131,1235,433,459]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.23" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="4.23">4.23 mm</quantity>
), the very densely punctate dorsum, the very narrow elytral interstriae, and the male genitalia (described below, 
<figureCitation box="[1197,1281,467,493]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–25" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[166,1426,196,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-28@64.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 24–25. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 24. Hydrochus accinctus n. sp. 25. Hydrochus amazonicus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043306/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[384,574,502,528]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spanglerorum">
<emphasis box="[384,574,502,528]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. spanglerorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group are recognized by the combination of the following characteristics: 1) large size, ca. 4.20–5.10; 2) head with very convex frons disc, with deep groove on each side of tumidity; 3) legs with densely, deeply punctate femora and tibiae; 4) 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[822,836,571,585]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">rd</superScript>
and 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[904,917,571,585]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">th</superScript>
elytral interstriae raised, costate to subcostate, throughout length, not additionally raised at usual area of callus; 5) male genitalia robust, lacking parameres and having articulated basal orifice. Three species are currently known, all in South America: 
<taxonomicName authority="Perkins, 2021" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2021" box="[1178,1320,641,666]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="accinctus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1178,1320,641,666]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. accinctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1329,1393,641,667]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1329,1393,641,667]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Perkins" authorityName="Perkins" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spanglerorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. spanglerorum</emphasis>
Perkins
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Perkins, 2021" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2021" box="[460,589,675,701]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colossus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[460,589,675,701]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. colossus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[596,658,675,701]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[596,658,675,701]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(habitus 
<figureCitation box="[763,829,675,701]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[158,1402,188,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-28@6.[152,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dorsal habitus of Hydrochus species in study area." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043263" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043263/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
; map 
<figureCitation box="[898,981,675,702]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–54" captionStartId="79.[151,264,1964,1988]" captionTargetBox="[218,1368,181,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-15@79.[218,1368,181,1941]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="FIGURES 53–54. Geographical distributions. 53. H spanglerorum species group. 54. H collaris species group." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043348/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,709,735]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Description</emphasis>
. Size: 
<typeStatus box="[420,518,710,736]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length to elytral apices) 4.23/1.60; head width 0.94; pronotum l/w 1.00/1.04; PA 0.96; PB 0.83; elytra 2.75/1.60. Habitus as illustrated (
<figureCitation box="[1092,1177,744,771]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–25" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[166,1426,196,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-28@64.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 24–25. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 24. Hydrochus accinctus n. sp. 25. Hydrochus amazonicus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043306/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Large (ca. 
<quantity box="[1319,1424,745,771]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.23" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="4.23">4.23 mm</quantity>
), elongate. Dorsum grey to very faint dull gold, with little or no iridescence. Legs dark brown except ventral surface of femora sometimes silver metallic with violet tint; all surfaces of femora densely coarsely punctate; tibiae with outer apical margin produced and bearing few short stout spines. Pronotum very densely, coarsely punctate. Elytral striae with deep round to slightly rectangular punctures; interstriae generally narrower than striae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Head densely, coarsely punctate; frons markedly raised in middle, with deep groove on each side of timidity; frontoclypeal suture absent.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Pronotum wider than long (L/W as ca. 1.00/1.04), widest at about distal 2/3; anterior margin arcuate; narrowed at base; sides denticulate, sinuate; punctures on pronotum moderately sized, deep, very dense; depressions deep in anterior, central depression margined laterally with rather sharp ridge, very shallow in posterior.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Elytra with strial punctures very deep and ca. 2–3x those on pronotum; interstriae ca. 1x width of striae; 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1376,1390,1091,1105]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">rd</superScript>
and 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[165,178,1125,1139]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">th</superScript>
interstriae raised, subcostate, throughout length, not additionally raised at usual area of callus; 9 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1245,1258,1125,1139]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">th</superScript>
interstria raised and overhanging 10 
<superScript attach="none" box="[374,387,1160,1174]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">th</superScript>
; apices truncate, with submarginal row of large, elongate punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Ventral characters: Mentum very coarsely punctate, with large central depression; submentum with two deep, transverse foveae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[374,455,1264,1291]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–25" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[166,1426,196,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-28@64.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 24–25. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 24. Hydrochus accinctus n. sp. 25. Hydrochus amazonicus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043306/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
) general characters: genitalia large, strongly sclerotized, very asymmetrical; basal piece elongate, with articulated orifice.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1112,1334,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,328,1360]" box="[199,1112,1334,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1334,1360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Etymology</emphasis>
. Named in reference to the very densely and deeply punctate dorsum.
</paragraph>
